Hematology
Thrombocytopenia
Thrombocytopenia is a condition in which there are a low number of platelets in the blood. Platelets are also called thrombocytes. Platelets are parts of blood that stick together and form a clot to help the body stop bleeding after an injury.
If you have too few platelets, your blood may have trouble clotting. This may cause you to bleed and bruise very easily. Some cases of thrombocytopenia are mild while others are more severe.
What are the causes?
This condition is caused by a low number of platelets in your blood. There are three main reasons for this:
Your body not making enough platelets. This may be caused by:
Bone marrow diseases. This include aplastic anemia, leukemia, and myelodysplastic anemia.
Congenital thrombocytopenia. This is a condition that is passed from parent to child (inherited).
Certain cancer treatments, including chemotherapy and radiation therapy.
Infections from bacteria or viruses.
Alcohol use disorder and alcoholism.
Platelets not being released in the blood. This is called platelet sequestration and it can happen due to:
An overactive spleen (hypersplenism). The spleen gathers up platelets from circulation, meaning that the platelets are not available to help with clotting your blood. The spleen can be enlarged because of scarring or other conditions.
Gaucher disease.
Your body destroying platelets too quickly. This may be caused by:
An autoimmune disease that causes immune thrombocytopenia (ITP). ITP is sometimes associated with other autoimmune conditions such as lupus.
Certain medicines, such as blood thinners.
Certain blood clotting or bleeding disorders.
Exposure to toxic chemicals, such as pesticides, lead, benzene, and arsenic.
Pregnancy.
What are the signs or symptoms?
Symptoms of this condition are the result of poor blood clotting. They will vary depending on how low the platelet counts are. Symptoms may include:
Bruising easily.
Bleeding from the mouth or nose.
Heavy menstrual periods.
Blood in the urine, stool (feces), or vomit.
Purplish-red discolorations on the skin (purpura).
A rash that looks like pinpoint, purplish-red spots (petechiae) on the lower legs.
How is this diagnosed?
This condition may be diagnosed with blood tests and a physical exam.
You may also have other tests, including:
A sample of bone marrow (biopsy) may be removed to look for the original cells that make platelets.
An ultrasound or CT scan of the abdomen to check for an enlarged spleen, enlarged lymph nodes, or liver problems.
How is this treated?
Treatment for this condition depends on the cause. Treatment may include:
Treatment of another condition that is causing the low platelet count.
Medicines to help protect your platelets from being destroyed.
A replacement (transfusion) of platelets to stop or prevent bleeding.
Surgery to remove the spleen.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider.
Do not take any medicines that contain aspirin or NSAIDs, such as ibuprofen. These medicines increase your risk for dangerous bleeding.
Activity
Avoid activities that could cause injury or bruising, and follow instructions about how to prevent falls.
Do not play contact sports. Ask your health care provider what activities are safe for you.
Take extra care to protect yourself from burns when ironing or cooking.
Take extra care not to cut yourself when you shave or when you use scissors, needles, knives, and other tools.
General instructions
Check your skin and the inside of your mouth for bruising or bleeding as told by your health care provider.
Wear a medical alert bracelet that says that you have a bleeding disorder. This can help you get the treatment you need in case of emergency.
Check your urine and stool for blood as told by your health care provider.
Do not drink alcohol. If you do drink alcohol, limit the amount that you drink.
Minimize contact with toxic chemicals.
Tell all your health care providers, including dental care providers and eye doctors, about your condition. Make sure to tell dental care providers before you have any procedure done, including dental cleanings.
Keep all follow-up visits. This is important.
Contact a health care provider if:
You have unexplained bruising.
You have new symptoms.
You have symptoms that get worse.
You have a fever.
Get help right away if:
You have severe bleeding from anywhere on your body.
You have blood in your vomit, urine, or stool.
You have an injury to your head.
You have a sudden, severe headache.
Summary
Thrombocytopenia is a condition in which you have a low number of platelets in the blood.
Platelets are parts of blood that stick together to form a clot.
Symptoms of this condition are the result of poor blood clotting and may include bruising easily, bleeding from the nose or mouth, petechiae, and purpura.
This condition may be diagnosed with blood tests and a physical exam.
Treatment for this condition depends on the cause.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Orthopedics
Acute Pain, Adult
Acute pain is a type of sudden pain that may last for just a few days or for as long as six months. It is often related to an illness, injury, or medical procedure. Acute pain may be mild, moderate, or severe.
Pain can make it hard for you to do your normal, daily activities. It can cause anxiety and lead to other problems if it is left untreated. Treatment depends on the cause and severity of your pain. Acute pain usually goes away once your injury has healed or you are no longer ill.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider.
Take the lowest dose of medicine for the shortest amount of time needed to relieve the pain.
If you are taking prescription pain medicine:
Do not stop taking the medicine suddenly. Talk to your health care provider about how and when to discontinue prescription medicine.
Do not take more pills than told by your health care provider even if your pain is severe.
Do not take other over-the-counter pain medicines in addition to prescription pain medicine unless told by your health care provider.
Ask your health care provider if the medicine requires you to avoid driving or using heavy machinery.
Ask your health care provider if the medicine can cause constipation. You may need to take these actions to prevent or treat constipation:
Drink enough fluid to keep your urine pale yellow.
Eat foods that are high in fiber, such as beans, whole grains, and fresh fruits and vegetables.
Take over-the-counter or prescription medicines.
Limit foods that are high in fat and processed sugars, such as fried or sweet foods.
Managing pain, stiffness, and swelling
If directed, put ice on the affected area. To do this:
Put ice in a plastic bag.
Place a towel between your skin and the bag.
Leave the ice on for 20 minutes, 23 times a day.
If directed, apply heat to the affected area as often as told by your health care provider. Use the heat source that your health care provider recommends, such as a moist heat pack or a heating pad.
Place a towel between your skin and the heat source.
Leave the heat on for 2030 minutes.
Remove the heat if your skin turns bright red. This is especially important if you are unable to feel pain, heat, or cold. You may have a greater risk of getting burned.
Activity
Rest as told by your health care provider.
Return to your normal activities as told by your health care provider. Ask your health care provider what activities are safe for you.
General instructions
Check your pain level as told by your health care provider.
Ask your health care provider if other strategies such as distraction, relaxation, or physical therapies can help your pain.
Keep all follow-up visits as told by your health care provider. This is important.
Contact a health care provider if:
Your pain is not controlled by medicine.
Your pain does not improve or gets worse.
You have side effects from pain medicines, such as vomiting or confusion.
Get help right away if you:
Have severe pain.
Have trouble breathing.
Lose consciousness.
Have chest pain or pressure that lasts for more than a few minutes, or if you have other symptoms along with chest pain, including if you:
Have pain or discomfort in one or both arms, your back, neck, jaw, or stomach.
Have shortness of breath.
Break out in a cold sweat.
Feel nauseous.
Become light-headed.
These symptoms may represent a serious problem that is an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
Acute pain may be mild, moderate, or severe. It usually goes away once your injury has healed or you are no longer ill.
Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider.
Ask your health care provider if the medicine prescribed to you can cause constipation.
Contact a health care provider if your pain is not controlled by medicine.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Infectious Disease
COPD Action Plan
A COPD action plan is a description of what to do when you have a flare (exacerbation) of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). Your action plan is a color-coded plan that lists the symptoms that indicate whether your condition is under control and what actions to take.
If you have symptoms in the green zone, it means you are doing well that day.
If you have symptoms in the yellow zone, it means you are having a bad day or an exacerbation.
If you have symptoms in the red zone, you need urgent medical care.
Follow the plan that you and your health care provider developed. Review your plan with your health care provider at each visit.
Red zone
Symptoms in this zone mean that you should get medical help right away. They include:
Feeling very short of breath, even when you are resting.
Not being able to do any activities because of poor breathing.
Not being able to sleep because of poor breathing.
Fever or shaking chills.
Feeling confused or very sleepy.
Chest pain.
Coughing up blood.
If you have any of these symptoms, call emergency services (911 in the U.S.) or go to the nearest emergency room.
Yellow zone
Symptoms in this zone mean that your condition may be getting worse. They include:
Feeling more short of breath than usual.
Having less energy for daily activities than usual.
Phlegm or mucus that is thicker than usual.
Needing to use your rescue inhaler or nebulizer more often than usual.
More ankle swelling than usual.
Coughing more than usual.
Feeling like you have a chest cold.
Trouble sleeping due to COPD symptoms.
Decreased appetite.
COPD medicines not helping as much as usual.
If you experience any "yellow" symptoms:
Keep taking your daily medicines as directed.
Use your quick-relief inhaler as told by your health care provider.
If you were prescribed steroid medicine to take by mouth (oral medicine), start taking it as told by your health care provider.
If you were prescribed an antibiotic medicine, start taking it as told by your health care provider. Do not stop taking the antibiotic even if you start to feel better.
Use oxygen as told by your health care provider.
Get more rest.
Do your pursed-lip breathing exercises.
Do not smoke. Avoid any irritants in the air.
If your signs and symptoms do not improve after taking these steps, call your health care provider right away.
Green zone
Symptoms in this zone mean that you are doing well. They include:
Being able to do your usual activities and exercise.
Having the usual amount of coughing, including the same amount of phlegm or mucus.
Being able to sleep well.
Having a good appetite.
Where to find more information:
You can find more information about COPD from:
American Lung Association, My COPD Action Plan: www.lung.org
COPD Foundation: www.copdfoundation.org
National Heart, Lung, & Blood Institute: www.nhlbi.nih.gov
Follow these instructions at home:
Continue taking your daily medicines as told by your health care provider.
Make sure you receive all the immunizations that your health care provider recommends, especially the pneumococcal and influenza vaccines.
Wash your hands often with soap and water. Have family members wash their hands too. Regular hand washing can help prevent infections.
Follow your usual exercise and diet plan.
Avoid irritants in the air, such as smoke.
Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco. These products include cigarettes, chewing tobacco, and vaping devices, such as e-cigarettes. If you need help quitting, ask your health care provider.
Summary
A COPD action plan tells you what to do when you have a flare (exacerbation) of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).
Follow each action plan for your symptoms. If you have any symptoms in the red zone, call emergency services (911 in the U.S.) or go to the nearest emergency room.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Pulmonary Medicine
Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a long-term (chronic) condition that affects the lungs. COPD is a general term that can be used to describe many different lung problems that cause lung inflammation and limit airflow, including chronic bronchitis and emphysema.
If you have COPD, your lung function will probably never return to normal. In most cases, it gets worse over time. However, there are steps you can take to slow the progression of the disease and improve your quality of life.
What are the causes?
This condition may be caused by:
Smoking. This is the most common cause.
Certain genes passed down through families.
What increases the risk?
The following factors may make you more likely to develop this condition:
Being exposed to secondhand smoke from cigarettes, pipes, or cigars.
Being exposed to chemicals and other irritants, such as fumes and dust in the work environment.
Having chronic lung conditions or infections.
What are the signs or symptoms?
Symptoms of this condition include:
Shortness of breath, especially during physical activity.
Chronic cough with a large amount of thick mucus. Sometimes, the cough may not have any mucus (dry cough).
Wheezing and rapid breathing.
Gray or bluish discoloration (cyanosis) of the skin, especially in the fingers, toes, or lips.
Feeling tired (fatigue).
Weight loss.
Chest tightness.
Frequent infections.
Episodes when breathing symptoms become much worse (exacerbations).
At the later stages of this disease, you may have swelling in the ankles, feet, or legs.
How is this diagnosed?
This condition is diagnosed based on:
Your medical history.
A physical exam.
You may also have tests, including:
Lung (pulmonary) function tests. This may include a spirometry test, which measures your ability to exhale properly.
Chest X-ray.
CT scan.
Blood tests.
How is this treated?
This condition may be treated with:
Medicines. These may include inhaled rescue medicines to treat acute exacerbations as well as medicines that you take long-term (maintenance medicines) to prevent flare-ups of COPD.
Bronchodilators help treat COPD by dilating the airways to allow increased airflow and make your breathing more comfortable.
Steroids can reduce airway inflammation and help prevent exacerbations.
Smoking cessation. If you smoke, your health care provider may ask you to quit, and may also recommend therapy or replacement products to help you quit.
Pulmonary rehabilitation. This may involve working with a team of health care providers and specialists, such as respiratory, occupational, and physical therapists.
Exercise and physical activity. These are beneficial for nearly all people with COPD.
Nutrition therapy to gain weight, if you are underweight.
Oxygen. Supplemental oxygen therapy is only helpful if you have a low oxygen level in your blood (hypoxemia).
Lung surgery or transplant.
Palliative care. This is to help people with COPD feel comfortable when treatment is no longer working.
Follow these instructions at home:
Medicines
Take over-the-counter and prescription medicines only as told by your health care provider. This includes inhaled medicines and pills.
Talk to your health care provider before taking any cough or allergy medicines. You may need to avoid certain medicines that dry out your airways.
Lifestyle
If you smoke, the most important thing that you can do is to stop smoking. Continuing to smoke will cause the disease to progress faster.
Do not use any products that contain nicotine or tobacco. These products include cigarettes, chewing tobacco, and vaping devices, such as e-cigarettes. If you need help quitting, ask your health care provider.
Avoid exposure to things that irritate your lungs, such as smoke, chemicals, and fumes.
Stay active, but balance activity with periods of rest. Exercise and physical activity will help you maintain your ability to do things you want to do.
Learn and use relaxation techniques to manage stress and to control your breathing.
Get the right amount of sleep and get quality sleep. Most adults need 7 or more hours per night.
Eat healthy foods. Eating smaller, more frequent meals and resting before meals may help you maintain your strength.
Controlled breathing
Learn and use controlled breathing techniques as directed by your health care provider. Controlled breathing techniques include:
Pursed lip breathing. Start by breathing in (inhaling) through your nose for 1 second. Then, purse your lips as if you were going to whistle and breathe out (exhale) through the pursed lips for 2 seconds.
Diaphragmatic breathing. Start by putting one hand on your abdomen just above your waist. Inhale slowly through your nose. The hand on your abdomen should move out. Then purse your lips and exhale slowly. You should be able to feel the hand on your abdomen moving in as you exhale.
Controlled coughing
Learn and use controlled coughing to clear mucus from your lungs. Controlled coughing is a series of short, progressive coughs. The steps of controlled coughing are:
1. Lean your head slightly forward.
2. Breathe in deeply using diaphragmatic breathing.
3. Try to hold your breath for 3 seconds.
4. Keep your mouth slightly open while coughing twice.
5. Spit any mucus out into a tissue.
6. Rest and repeat the steps once or twice as needed.
General instructions
Make sure you receive all the vaccines that your health care provider recommends, especially the pneumococcal and influenza vaccines. Preventing infection and hospitalization is very important when you have COPD.
Drink enough fluid to keep your urine pale yellow, unless you have a medical condition that requires fluid restriction.
Use oxygen therapy and pulmonary rehabilitation if told by your health care provider. If you require home oxygen therapy, ask your health care provider whether you should purchase a pulse oximeter to measure your oxygen level at home.
Work with your health care provider to develop a COPD action plan. This will help you know what steps to take if your condition gets worse.
Keep other chronic health conditions under control as told by your health care provider.
Avoid extreme temperature and humidity changes.
Avoid contact with people who have an illness that spreads from person to person (is contagious), such as viral infections or pneumonia.
Keep all follow-up visits. This is important.
Contact a health care provider if:
You are coughing up more mucus than usual.
There is a change in the color or thickness of your mucus.
Your breathing is more labored than usual.
Your breathing is faster than usual.
You have difficulty sleeping.
You need to use your rescue medicines or inhalers more often than expected.
You have trouble doing routine activities such as getting dressed or walking around the house.
Get help right away if:
You have shortness of breath while you are resting.
You have shortness of breath that prevents you from:
Being able to talk.
Performing your usual physical activities.
You have chest pain lasting longer than 5 minutes.
Your skin color is more blue (cyanotic) than usual.
You measure low oxygen saturations for longer than 5 minutes with a pulse oximeter.
You have a fever.
You feel too tired to breathe normally.
These symptoms may represent a serious problem that is an emergency. Do not wait to see if the symptoms will go away. Get medical help right away. Call your local emergency services (911 in the U.S.). Do not drive yourself to the hospital.
Summary
Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a long-term (chronic) condition that affects the lungs.
Your lung function will probably never return to normal. In most cases, it gets worse over time. However, there are steps you can take to slow the progression of the disease and improve your quality of life.
Treatment for COPD may include taking medicines, quitting smoking, pulmonary rehabilitation, and changes to diet and exercise. As the disease progresses, you may need oxygen therapy, a lung transplant, or palliative care.
To help manage your condition, do not smoke, avoid exposure to things that irritate your lungs, stay up to date on all vaccines, and follow your health care provider's instructions for taking medicines.
This information is not intended to replace advice given to you by your health care provider. Make sure you discuss any questions you have with your health care provider.

Open Hernia Repair, Adult, Care After
This sheet gives you information about how to care for yourself after your procedure. Your health care provider may also give you more specific instructions. If you have problems or questions, contact your health care provider.
What can I expect after the procedure?
After the procedure, it is common to have:
Mild discomfort.
Slight bruising.
Minor swelling.
Pain in the abdomen.
Follow these instructions at home:
Incision care
What did we do: We fixed a hernia, which is a weakness in your abdominal wall. We may have used mesh to help reinforce your abdominal wall. We closed the skin with sutures that will absorb, and covered with a dressing.
-Diet: as tolerated. Drink plenty of water.
-Activity:. No lifting more than 10 pounds, doing push-ups/pull-ups/sit-ups, doing activities that strain your abdominal wall for 6 weeks after surgery. Gentle stretching and light cardio activities can be resumed after your first post-operative visit at the 2-week mark. It is important to follow these instructions to allow your tissue time to heal.
-Wound care: You have surgical glue covering your wound and an outer dressing on top of that. You may shower starting 24 hours post-operatively. If you have an outer dressing, you may remove it at that time as well. The surgical glue covering your wound will fall off in its own time. Do not pick at your wound. Do not cover your wound with lotion/cream. Keep wound clean and dry at all times. Do not immerse your wound in water for 4 weeks in pools, baths, hot tubs, ocean, etc.
-Symptoms to expect: General area may ache for several weeks following surgery, but should slowly improve. You may have a ridge underneath your scar, which will soften over time. If you had laparoscopic surgery, you may have an ache in your shoulders, which is from the gas we used, and it will resolve in a few days.
-Symptoms to be concerned about (including but not limited to): fevers/chills, nausea/vomiting, chest pain/shortness of breath, inability to urinate or have a bowel movement, wound turning red/swollen/draining fluid or pus, bleeding from wound, pain worsening instead of improving. If any of these events happen or you are concerned, call or come to the general surgery clinic for evaluation.
-Pain control:
1. You were given a narcotic (Oxy IR) for pain control initially following surgery, which you can take up to every 4-6 hours. Narcotics impair your ability to make decisions and operate machinery and make you sleepy. You will likely need narcotics for at least the first week or two, then you may taper as you see fit.
2. You were given a stool softener to take following surgery because narcotics and the medications you get during surgery also make you constipated. You may take the stool softener up to twice a day. Decrease frequency if you are having loose stools. Come to medical if you need more medication to help you have soft stools.
3. You were given Motrin to take following surgery for pain control. Start taking it 1 day after surgery and I recommend you take one pill every 8 hours for the first week or two, even if you are not having pain, to decrease the amount of narcotics you need. You may taper as you see fit.
4. You were also given Tylenol for pain control. I recommend taking 650 mg of Tylenol every 8 hours. Do not take over 3000mg of Tylenol in a 24 hour period.
5. You may use ice or heat over wound in 15 minute increments to help with pain. Always use a barrier to prevent skin injury from direct ice or heat application to skin.
